                            <comment id="122698" author="olivergierke" created="Fri, 25 Dec 2015 17:05:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t think we&apos;re going to introduce this as using JSR-303 annotations on domain types is bad practice in the first place. It creates incentives to build weak domain objects that rely on annotations to &quot;enforce&quot; core object responsibilities instead of implementing those constraint within the very object. See this &lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;pull request&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;(&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/spring-guides/gs-validating-form-input/pull/12#issue-123655110&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://github.com/spring-guides/gs-validating-form-input/pull/12#issue-123655110&lt;/a&gt;) in a related project for more details on the rationale.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="122699" author="agraphie" created="Fri, 25 Dec 2015 20:55:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;While I understand (more or less) the rational, where would you put the annotations in this example? Would you split it in two objects, one having annotations?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Imho this is a reasonable idea, but maybe I don&apos;t understand the implications properly.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="122704" author="augusto.altman" created="Sat, 26 Dec 2015 15:33:25 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;First of all thank both for the quick christmas answer &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/images/icons/emoticons/biggrin.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;, and sorry for the duplicate bug I don&apos;t understand what happened.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Back to our bussines, Oliver I believe I understand what is your point here, but then I have three questions:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;How can I enrich my JSON Schemas? Basically I need richer JSON Schemas to perform some client side validations by using for example &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/akidee/schema.js&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;schema.js&lt;/a&gt; in order to tell the user when some field contains errors before sending the request to the API. Of course server side validations will be performed as well, nevertheless doing also client side validations ensure a much better user experience for a web application consuming my API. I want to avoid hardcoding the validation rules in the client side.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;What is the recomended way to perform validations over my API? I mean, if using JSR-303 over my entities (jpa) is not a good idea because they are part of the domain model, then how can I ensure that, for example, whatever comes in a HTTP-PUT request is properly formatted?&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Even Hibernate provides their own validation annotations (both from the JSR-303 spec and their own custom validators) for be used on domain types, check &lt;a href=&quot;http://hibernate.org/validator/documentation/getting-started/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;this&lt;/a&gt;... are they basically encouraging bad practices?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Clemens, I put the validations over the Client Entity. Of course this entity is &quot;exposed&quot; in the REST API through some Spring data rest respository that I did not include in the example code above. My rationale here is to be able to perform client side validations as well, without hardcoding the validations rules on the client side. Then enriching the JSON schema with the proper rules taken from the server side validator sounds as a good idea (at first glance)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thank you both again. Sorry for the verbose answer.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="123166" author="augusto.altman" created="Wed, 20 Jan 2016 19:39:28 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Is there any update on this?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="128136" author="zeppjan" created="Tue, 22 Mar 2016 16:36:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I would appreciate a solution or answer to this issue too, because&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;we are searching for the exact same feature for some weeks now and were about to implement it by ourself, extending Spring classes (which is hardly possible due to class restrictions) and even writing our own JsonSchema... though we haven&apos;t start yet and just tried to find out which classes to extend or proxy with AOP,&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;I saw that the actual JsonSchema encourages using it for validation constraints although I have to admit that they don&apos;t refer to Java in this context not to mention JSR-303 (&lt;a href=&quot;http://json-schema.org/examples.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://json-schema.org/examples.html&lt;/a&gt;) and&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;how we are supposed to implement validation with e.g. form-backing objects in Spring DATA REST to conform to best pratices? In my undertanding this would imply implementing controllers - which are handled nicely by SDR by default - for all HTTP methods changing an domain object, form backing objects and services again just to use JSR-303 validation and separate JSR-303 from domain objects.&lt;br/&gt;
Or would you forgo JSR-303 annotations at all and use the SDR validation described in the reference documentation &lt;a href=&quot;http://docs.spring.io/spring-data/rest/docs/2.4.2.RELEASE/reference/html/#validation&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://docs.spring.io/spring-data/rest/docs/2.4.2.RELEASE/reference/html/#validation&lt;/a&gt;?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;


&lt;p&gt;All in all I still think that it is a great idea to expose validation constraints by the API because it simplifies to keep backend and frontend validation consistent.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Best regards,&lt;br/&gt;
Jan&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
